Q1. What does the replace() method do in Python? How many arguments does it take?
Ans: replace() replaces one substring with another substring. It mainly takes 2 arguments.

Q2. What is the difference between lstrip(), rstrip(), and strip()? Give one example of each.
Ans:
lstrip() removes spaces from the left side.
rstrip() removes spaces from the right side.
strip() removes spaces from both sides.

Example:

"  hello".lstrip()
"hello  ".rstrip()
"  hello  ".strip()

Q3. What does split() return? What is the default delimiter if none is provided?
Ans: split() returns a list of strings. Default delimiter is space.

Q4. What is the difference between capitalize() and title()? Give one example where their output is different.
Ans: capitalize() makes only the first letter uppercase, while title() makes the first letter of every word uppercase.

Example:

"hello world".capitalize()
"hello world".title()

Q5. What does swapcase() do? What will "Hello World".swapcase() return?
Ans: swapcase() changes uppercase to lowercase and lowercase to uppercase.
Output: "hELLO wORLD"

Q6. What is the difference between chr() and ord()? Give one example of each.
Ans: chr() converts ASCII value to character, while ord() converts character to ASCII value.

Examples:

chr(65)
ord('A')

Q7. What does the str() built-in function do? Give one real-life example of when you would use it.
Ans: str() converts a value into string type.
Example: Converting a number before concatenating with text.

Q8. What does join() do? Which object calls join() -- the list or the separator string?
Ans: join() combines elements of a list into a single string. The separator string calls join().

Q9. What is the difference between split() and partition()?
Ans: split() divides a string into multiple parts, while partition() divides into exactly 3 parts.

Q10. What does strip() remove from a string? Does it remove whitespace from the middle of a string?
Ans: strip() removes whitespace from the beginning and end only. It does not remove spaces from the middle.

Q11. What is the difference between lower() and upper()? Do they change the original string?
Ans: lower() converts to lowercase and upper() converts to uppercase. They do not change the original string.

Q12. What is the difference between str(), int(), float(), and complex() in Python? Which category do they belong to -- methods or built-in functions?
Ans:
str() converts to string
int() converts to integer
float() converts to float
complex() converts to complex number
They are built-in functions.

Q13. What will int("25") return? What will float("25") return? What is the difference in output?
Ans:
int("25") returns 25
float("25") returns 25.0
Difference is integer and decimal output.

Q14. Can you convert a float to int using int()? What happens to the decimal part -- does it round off or truncate?
Ans: Yes. The decimal part is truncated.

Q15. What does complex() do? Give one example of a complex number and how str() converts it.
Ans: complex() creates a complex number.
Example: 3+4j
str(3+4j) converts it into string form.

Q16. What will str(10), str(10.5), and str(10+4j) return? What type will each result be?
Ans:
str(10) returns "10"
str(10.5) returns "10.5"
str(10+4j) returns "(10+4j)"
All results are of string type.

Q17. What does partition() return when the separator is NOT found in the string?
Ans: It returns the original string and two empty strings.

Q18. What is the difference between replace() and split()? Can both be used to remove a word from a string?
Ans: replace() substitutes text, while split() divides the string. Yes, both can help remove words in different ways.

Q19. What will "hello".upper().swapcase() return? Explain method chaining with this example.
Ans: Output is "hello".
Method chaining means calling multiple methods one after another.

Q20. If chr(65) gives "A", what will chr(66), chr(67), and chr(90) give? What concept does this relate to?
Ans:
chr(66) gives "B"
chr(67) gives "C"
chr(90) gives "Z"
This relates to ASCII values.